@node Simple HTTP server
@section Simple HTTP server
@anchor{#simple-http-server}
Run this code in your console:

@verbatim
guile -c "(use-modules (artanis artanis))(init-server)(run)"
## You'll see this screen:
Anytime you want to quit just try Ctrl+C, thanks!
http://127.0.0.1:3000
@end verbatim

Assuming there's a file named "index.html" in the current path. Now you may try @url{http://localhost:3000/index.html} in your browser. It's just simply fetching static file by the URL: @url{http://localhost:3000/path/filename}

@node Try simple URL remapping
@section Try simple URL remapping
@anchor{#try-simple-url-remapping}
Type these code in Guile REPL:

@verbatim
(use-modules (artanis artanis))
(init-server)
(get "/hello" (lambda () "hello world"))
(run #:port 8080)
@end verbatim

Now you can visit @url{http://localhost:8080/hello} with your browser, and (hopefully) see the result.

/If you encounter "[EXCEPTION] @emph{favicon.ico is abnormal request" , please just ignore that warning.}

Let me explain the code:

@itemize
@item
@emph{line 1:} Load GNU Artanis module, (artanis artanis) is the name.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
@emph{line 3:} The first argument @emph{get} is GNU Artanis' API correspondence to the GET method of the HTTP protocol. The second argument "/hello" is the URL rule to register showing in the address line of e.g. firefox. The third argument is the handler which will be triggered if the registered URL rule is hit.

@item
@emph{line 4:} Run the GNU Artanis web server, and listen on socket port 8080.

@end itemize

You may type Ctrl+C to quit and stop the server, see also the message printed on the screen accordingly.

@node More complex URL remapping
@section More complex URL remapping
@anchor{#more-complex-url-remapping}
Try this code:

@verbatim
(use-modules (artanis artanis))
(init-server)
(get "/hello/:who"
  (lambda (rc)
    (format #f "<p>hello ~a</p> " (params rc "who"))))
(run #:port 8080)
@end verbatim

Now you can try @url{http://localhost:8080/hello/artanis} in your browser.

There are two differences compared to the simpler example:

@itemize
@item
1. The special rule, "@code{/hello/:who}", @emph{:who} means you can use @emph{params} to refer to the value of the par of the URL with the key "who". Like: @code{(params rc "who")}.

@item
2. You may have noticed that the handler is being defined as an anonymous function with @emph{lambda} has one argument @emph{rc}. It means @emph{route context} which preserves all the related context information. Many GNU Artanis APIs need it, e.g. @emph{params}.

@end itemize

And @emph{format} is a Scheme lib function. It is similar to @emph{sprintf} in the C language, which outputs text with a formatted pattern. The second argument #f (means FALSE) indicates that the formatted output should be returned in a string rather than printed out.

@node Regex in URL remapping
@section Regex in URL remapping
@anchor{#regex-in-url-remapping}
You can use regular expressions as a URL rule argument.

@verbatim
(use-modules (artanis artanis))
(init-server)
(get "/.+\\.(png|gif|jpeg)" static-page-emitter)
(run #:port 8080)
@end verbatim

@emph{static-page-emitter} is a GNU Artanis API that sends a static file (images, data files) to the client.

@node Database operating
@section Database operating
@anchor{#database-operating}
GNU Artanis supports mysql/postgresql/sqlite3. We use mysql as an example here.

Please ensure that your DB service was started before you run this code.

@strong{@emph{If you encounter any problems, it's very likely it's with your DB config.}}

You can use a DB (such as mysql) with GUI tools such as "adminer", independently of the running web-server, e.g. artanis-based.

@verbatim
(use-modules (artanis artanis))
(init-server)
(define conn (connect-db 'mysql #:db-username "your_db_username"
                         #:db-name "your_db_name" #:db-passwd "your_passwd"))
(define mtable (map-table-from-DB conn))
((mtable 'create 'Persons '((name varchar 10)
                            (age integer)
                            (email varchar 20)))
 'valid?)
;; ==> #t
(mtable 'set 'Persons #:name "nala" #:age 20 #:email "nala@artanis.dev")
(mtable 'get 'Persons #:columns '(name email))
;; ==> ((("name" . "nala") ("email" . "nala@artanis.com")))
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
@emph{map-table-from-DB} is the GNU Artanis API handling tables in a DB. Here, we define this mapping as the var @emph{mtable}.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
We can use @emph{mtable} to handle tables, you can get the values from a table with the 'get command.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
@emph{mtable} is a function which accepts the first argument as a command, say 'create, which is a command to create a new table. 'set is used to insert/update values in the table. And the 'get command to fetch the values of specific columns.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
The second argument of @emph{mtable} is the name of the table as you can guess. Please note that it is case sensitive, while the column name isn't.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
The @emph{@strong{'create}} command returns a function too, which also accepts an argument as a command. Here, we use the @emph{@strong{'valid?}} command to check if the table has been created successfully.
@end itemize

This was just a simple introduction. You may read the DB section in this manual for details.

Of course, you can use DB in your web application.

@verbatim
(get "/dbtest" #:conn #t ; apply for a DB connection from pool
     (lambda (rc)
       (let ((mtable (map-table-from-DB (:conn rc))))
         (object->string
          (mtable 'get 'Persons #:columns '(name email))))))

(run #:use-db? #t #:dbd 'mysql #:db-username "your_db_username"
     #:db-name "your_db_name" #:db-passwd "your_passwd" #:port 8080)
@end verbatim

Now, try loading @url{http://localhost:8080/dbtest} in your browser.

Here is quick explanation:

@itemize
@item
The keyword-value pair @code{#:conn #t} means applying for a DB connection from connection-pool. Then you can use @code{(:conn rc)} to get the allocated connection for DB operations.

@item
Finally, the handler needs to return a string as the HTTP response body, so in this example,

@end itemize

we have to use the Guile API @emph{object->string} to convert the query result into a string.

@emph{Exercise: Return a beautiful table in HTML rather than using object->string.}

