@node Emit a Response
@section Emit a Response
@anchor{#emit-a-response}

@verbatim
(response-emit body #:status 200 #:headers '() #:mtime (current-time))
@end verbatim

@strong{body} is the response body, it can be a bytevector or literal string (in HTML).

@code{#:status} is the HTTP status, 200 in default, which means OK.

@code{#:headers} lets you specify custom HTTP headers. The headers must follow a certain format. Please read @uref{http://www.gnu.org/software/guile/manual/html_node/HTTP-Headers.html#Response-Headers,Response Headers} for details.

@code{#:mtime} specifies the modified time in the response. GNU Artanis will generate it for you when not defined.

@verbatim
(emit-response-with-file filename [headers <- '()])
@end verbatim

@strong{filename} is the filename to be sent as a response.

[headers] is the custom HTTP headers.

@node Running the server
@section Running the server
@anchor{#running-the-server}

@verbatim
(run #:host #f #:port #f #:debug #f #:use-db? #f
     #:dbd #f #:db-username #f #:db-passwd #f #:db-name #f)
@end verbatim

@emph{keywords with the value #f, as default, will get the values from the config file.}

But you can define them as well.

@code{#:host} the hostname.

@code{#:port} the socket port of the server.

@code{#:debug} set #t if you want to enable debug mode. Logs will be more verbose.

@code{#:use-db?} set #t if you want to use DB, and GNU Artanis will initialize DB connections.

@code{#:dbd} choose a dbd. These are the supported three: mysql, postgresql, and sqlite3.

@code{#:db-username} the username of your DB server.

@code{#:db-passwd} the DB password for the user above.

@code{#:db-name} the DB name to use.

