@node Introduction to URL remapping
@section Introduction to URL remapping
@anchor{#introduction-to-url-remapping}
URL remapping is used to modify a web URL's appearance to provide short, pretty or fancy, search engine friendly URLs. It's largely used in modern WAFs(web application framework) to provide RESTful web APIs.

@node URL handling
@section URL handling
@anchor{#url-handling}
According to RFC2616, the methods include GET, POST, etc. However, because of the naming conflict, GNU Artanis provides the methods by this list:

@itemize
@item
get
@item
post
@item
put
@item
patch
@item
page-delete
@item
page-options
@end itemize

@emph{In GNU Artanis the HEAD method is handled by the server, so you can't define specific handlers directly for it within GNU Artanis.}

Usage:

@verbatim
(method rule handler)
@end verbatim

And the handler could be one of two types, depending on your needs:

@verbatim
(lambda ()
  ...
  ret)

(lambda (rc)
  ...
  ret)
@end verbatim

@strong{ret} also has two types:

@itemize
@item
1. literal string as the returned response body

@item
2. See @emph{Emit a Response}

@end itemize

@verbatim
(get "/hello" (lambda () "hello world"))
@end verbatim

For a POST method:

@verbatim
(post "/auth" (lambda (rc) ...))
@end verbatim

@node OPTIONS method
@section OPTIONS method
@anchor{#options-method}
OPTIONS method is used to return the other methods supported by the server-side at the given URL. By default in GNU Artanis, for a specified URL, every method whose handler was registerted would be added to its own OPTIONS list.

If you want to deny certain methods for security consideration, you may need to set @strong{server.allowedmethods} in config.

@strong{NOTE:} If you're not trying to use Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS), then you may not need to care about it.

@node Get parameters from a URL
@section Get parameters from a URL
@anchor{#get-parameters-from-a-url}

@verbatim
(params rc name)
;; e.g
(get "/hello/:who" (lambda (rc) (params rc "who")))
@end verbatim

@node Redirecting
@section Redirecting
@anchor{#redirecting}

@verbatim
(redirect-to rc path #:status 301 #:type '(text/html) #:headers '())
;; e.g
(get "/aaa" (lambda (rc) (redirect-to rc "/bbb")))
(get "/bbb" (lambda () "ok bbb"))
@end verbatim

The @strong{path} could be 2 possible patterns:

@itemize
@item
URI created by @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/guile/manual/html_node/URIs.html,string->uri}. For example, @code{(redirect-to rc (string->uri "https://nalaginrut.com/feed/atom"))}.
@item
A relative path which will finally be converted to absolute URL append the @strong{host.addr}. For example, @code{(redirect-to rc "/login")}.
@end itemize

@strong{NOTE:} redirect-to will always use absolute URL implicitly. Although the standard supports relative URL, there maybe some problems when you're behind a proxy. So we use absolute URL to avoid these issues.

@node Route context
@chapter Route context
@anchor{#route-context}
Route context is a struct type object which encapsulates the necessary information for the server from the current request context. We named it @emph{route} because it's related to the route of @emph{URL remapping}. Usually it's passed to the page handler as a unique argument. It's supposed to provide sufficient data about the current request.

@verbatim
(HTTP-METHOD URL-rule (lambda (<route-context>) ...))
;; e.g:
(get "/hello" (lambda (rc) "world")) ; rc is <route-context> type
@end verbatim

@menu
* Route context APIs::
@end menu

@node Route context APIs
@section Route context APIs
@anchor{#route-context-apis}

@verbatim
(rc-path <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the requested path, that is to say, the actual URI visited by the client.
@end itemize

@verbatim
;; e.g
(get "/hello/world" (lambda (rc) (rc-path rc)))
;; visit localhost:3000/hello/world or from any port you specified
;; the result is "/hello/world".
(get "/hello/:who" (lambda (rc) (rc-path rc)))
;; visit localhost:3000/hello/world or from any port you specified
;; the result is "/hello/world".
@end verbatim

@verbatim
(rc-req <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the current HTTP request wrapped in record-type. About HTTP request please see @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/guile/manual/html_node/Requests.html,HTTP Request}. It stores HTTP request of Guile.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-body <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the current request body:
@itemize
@item
For a regular HTTP request, the body should be a bytevector;
@item
For a Websocket request, the body should be @emph{Websocket frame} as a record-type.
@end itemize

@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-method <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the current requested HTTP method.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-conn <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the current DB connection if you've requested one, please checkout @emph{DB shortcut}.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-qt <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get query table, which is a key-value list parsed from @emph{query string}.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-handler <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the current request handler. The tricky part is that you can only get this handler within this handler unless you can go no where to run @emph{rc-handler} correctly.
@itemize
@item
It's on your own risk to use this API. But now that we have powerful first class lambda, you may do some magic. Well, depends on you.
@end itemize

@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-mtime <route-context>) ; getter
(rc-mtime! <route-context>) ; setter
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
You may set it in the handler to return you customized modified time. For static pages, the mtime is set automatically. But sometimes people may want to set it in a dynamic generated page.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-cookie <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
The cookies parsed from request header.
@end itemize

@verbatim
(rc-set-cookie! <route-context>)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Set response cookie from server side. If you want to return cookies to the client, please use it.

@verbatim
(get-header rc 'Authorization)
(get-header rc 'X-My-Custom-Header)
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
Get the value of a request header in the current route context.
@end itemize

@end itemize

There're other APIs in @emph{route-context}, but they're largely used for internals of Artanis, rarely useful for users. So we don't list them here.

