@node Controllers/Views
@section Controllers/Views
@anchor{#controllersviews}
Let's make a controller named @emph{article}:

@verbatim
art draw controller article show edit
@end verbatim

@emph{show} and @emph{edit} are the name of methods for the controller named @emph{article}.

This will generate both a @strong{controller} and a @strong{view} for @emph{article}:

@verbatim
drawing    controller article
working    Controllers `article.scm'
create     app/controllers/article.scm
working    Views `article'
create     app/views/article/show.html.tpl
create     app/views/article/edit.html.tpl
@end verbatim

These three files are generated:

@verbatim
app/controllers/article.scm
app/views/article/show.html.tpl
app/views/article/edit.html.tpl
@end verbatim

Based on this, the controller @emph{article} will have two methods mapped to the URL rule, @emph{show} and @emph{edit}. As part of the @emph{view} component. An HTML template is generated for each method. For the @emph{show} method for example, the view file @strong{show.html.tpl} is created. For the @emph{controller} component, you get a @emph{show} method handler, as:

@verbatim
(article-define show
  ;; (method get/post/put/patch/page-delete/page-options) ; method type
  ;; (options ...) ; see below for options
  (lambda (rc)
    "<h1>This is article#show</h1><p>Find me in app/views/article/show.html.tpl</p>"
    ;; TODO: add controller method `show'
    ;; uncomment this line if you want to render view from template
    ;; (view-render "show")
    ))
@end verbatim

Of course, you're free to use or not use these templates. If you want to use the @emph{view template}, just uncomment the last line @code{(view-render "show")}.

@itemize
@item
(options shortcuts @dots{}) see @emph{Shortcuts} for details.
@end itemize

@strong{NOTE:} The views template generated by MVC will defaultly announce FreeJS. The reason was well explained in @emph{The Javascript Trap}. It's optional, you may remove it with your free will, but I put it there in the hope that you can support free software with us.

For more detail about template in Views, please see @emph{Layouts and Rendering in GNU Artanis}.

