@node Create models
@subsection Create models
@anchor{#create-models}
A Model a is usually connected to the same named Controller. However, in practical, users may create multiple Models for one Controller. Hence, GNU Artanis creates Model outside Controller, rather than autogenerate a Model when creating Controller.

@verbatim
art create mytest
cd mytest

# Create model
art draw model user
# drawing    model user
# working    Models `user.scm'

# check result
ls app/models/
# user.scm
@end verbatim

In this case, we created a Model named @strong{@strong{user}}. A file named @strong{@strong{user.scm}} is in @strong{@strong{app/models}} now, let's open it:

@verbatim
(import (artanis mvc model))
;; Model user definition of mytest
;; Please add your license header here.
;; This file is generated automatically by GNU Artanis.
(create-artanis-model user) ; DO NOT REMOVE THIS LINE!!!
@end verbatim

It's done! These code are self-explain.

Next, let's try to define an @strong{@strong{user}} table.

@node Define table in Model
@subsection Define table in Model
@anchor{#define-table-in-model}
In this example, we craete a table like this:

@verbatim
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
| Field | Type        | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |
|-------+-------------+------+-----+---------+----------------|
| id    | auto        | NO   | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |
| name  | char-field  | NO   |     | NULL    |                |
| email | char-field  | NO   |     | NULL    |                |
+-------------------------------------------------------------+
@end verbatim

For Model definition syntax in GNU Artanis, we have:

@verbatim
(create-artanis-model
 user  ; model name
 (:deps) ; deps list
 (id auto (#:primary-key))
 (name char-field (#:not-null #:maxlen 128))
 (email char-field (#:not-null #:maxlen 128))
 )
@end verbatim

@strong{@strong{NOTE:}} If you have definition, and you've imported in any controller, when booting GNU Artanis with src_scheme[:exports code](art work), then the defined table will be created automatically in the specified database. Don't worry, it will be created only once.

@strong{@strong{NOTE:}} The Model name @strong{@strong{must}} be the same with Model file's name.

@node Tables dependencies
@subsection Tables dependencies
@anchor{#tables-dependencies}
Since the tables will be auto-created when booting the server core, however, the MVC doesn't know the dependency chain. To help the auto-creation doing correct work, you may want to specify the table dependencies in the table definition:

For example, you have another Model named @strong{@strong{article}} which is designed for your blog system. Obviously, it's related to @strong{@strong{user}} table since every article requires at least one user as an author.

@verbatim
(create-artanis-model
 article  ; model name
 (:deps user) ; deps list
 (id auto (#:primary-key))
 (author_id tinyint (#:not-null))
 (title char-field (#:not-null #:maxlen 128))
 (timestamp bigint (#:unsigned #:not-null))
 )
@end verbatim

You may realized we've added src_scheme[:exports code]((:deps user)) to hint the MVC system that @strong{@strong{article}} table should be created after @strong{@strong{user}} table. So when it meets @strong{@strong{article}} Model during booting, it'll make sure to create @strong{@strong{user}} then @strong{@strong{article}}.

@strong{@strong{NOTE:}}: src_scheme[:exports code]((:deps models_list @dots{})) @strong{@strong{NOTE:}} This feature is useful when you do DB migration.

