@node Templating
@section Templating
@anchor{#templating}
Templating provides a way to mix programmatic code into HTML.

@node Templating for Pythoners
@section Templating for Pythoners
@anchor{#templating-for-pythoners}
If you're familiar with Django, which implemented a DSL(Domain Specific Language) to express presentation rather than program logic. Templating in GNU Artanis follows a different philosophy.

Templating in GNU Artanis, is just writing Scheme code in the HTML document. Why? Because of the philosophy of FP(Functional Programming), everything is a function. So, @code{(filesizeformat size)} is easy enough to grasp for anyone with scheme experience. It's just a simple function calling in prefix-notation. There's no need to implement DSL like @code{size|filesizeformat} to increase the complexity of code. Let alone the syntax is very different from Python.

The syntax @code{size | filesizeformat} follows postfix-notation, used in stack-based languages, say Forth. Such a language used to delegate another programming paradigm named concatenative programming. It's very different from the paradigm of Scheme (functional programming), and the paradigm of Python (imperative programming).

The philosophy of GNU Artanis templating is to bring it into correspondence with the paradigm of the language. And reduce unnecessary complexities. @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KISS_principle,KISS}.

@node Templating for Rubyists
@section Templating for Rubyists
@anchor{#templating-for-rubyists}
Templating in GNU Artanis looks very similar to Rails.

The Rails code:

@verbatim
<% if( @fullscreen == 1 ) %>
<%= "<div class='full'><p>...</p></div>" %>
<% end %>
@end verbatim

And the same function in GNU Artanis code:

@verbatim
<% (if (= fullscreen 1) %>
       <% "<div class='full'><p>...</p></div>" %>
       <% ) %>
@end verbatim

@node Templating APIs
@section Templating APIs
@anchor{#templating-apis}

@verbatim
(tpl->response filename/sxml [environment <- (the-environment)] [escape? <- #f])

(tpl->html filename/sxm [environment <- (the-environment)] [escape? <- #f])
@end verbatim

@emph{The difference is that tpl->html returns a string, but tpl->response returns an HTTP object response.}

[environment] is the environment you want to use. We often ignore it. If you want to ref some vars defined outside your template string, you need to pass this variable.

[escape?] If you want to char-escape the HTML with the returned string, set it to #t.

There are two main ways of writing templates:

@node Embedded Templates
@section Embedded Templates
@anchor{#embedded-templates}
Example: Write a tpl file named "my.tpl":

@verbatim
<html>
  <p> <%= "This is tpl test!" %> </p>
  <p> <% (format #t "And this is ~a" (getcwd)) %> </p>
  <p> <%= external-var %> </p>
</html>
@end verbatim

The filename extension ".tpl" is mandatory when using the MVC. Since the MVC will find the template by detecting controller name automatically.

If you don't use the MVC, and are rather writing all in one script file loading GNU Artanis modules. Then you don't need to follow this rule.

@strong{NOTE:} Don't wrap code in double-quotes, for example:

@verbatim
<a href="<%= my-url %>">click me</a> <!-- Wrong! -->
<a href=<%= my-url %> >click me</a> <!-- Correct! -->
@end verbatim

If you need to output a double-quoted string, please use @code{object->string} to convert in Scheme first.

@verbatim
<a href=<%= (object->string my-url) %> >click me</a> <!-- If my-url is not properly quoted -->
@end verbatim

@verbatim
(get "/test"
  (lambda (rc)
    (let ((external-var 123))
      (tpl->response "my.tpl" (the-environment)))))
(run #:port 8080)
@end verbatim

In this case, make sure to put my.tpl in the same path as your GNU Artanis code.

Since @strong{external-var} is defined outside the file "my.tpl", and it's bound in @emph{let} with 123, you have to pass (the-environment). Or the template render will complain aobut not being able to find the variable @strong{external-var}.

If you don't need to refer to any external vars, just use @code{(tpl->response "file.tpl")}.

To test, access @url{http://localhost:3000/test} in your browser.

