@node Template special commands
@subsection Template special commands
@anchor{#template-special-commands}
GNU Artanis provides special helper commands.

Please notice that GNU Artanis constrains the path of sources in the application directory for security reasons. The resources files, CSS, JS etc, should be put int @strong{pub} directory in the application directory, or the client won't be able to access them.

These special commands are useful to expand the path for you, and they should be added into the tamplate file, for example:

@verbatim
<html>
  <head>
    <@icon favicon.ico %>
      <@js functions.js %>
        <@css blog.css %>
  </head>

  <@include sidebar.html %>

    <body>
      ...
    </body>
</html>
@end verbatim

@strong{NOTE:} The command name is prefixed with @strong{@@}, as, @strong{@@include}, @strong{@@css}, etc. Please do not seperate the @strong{@@}, or it will throw exception.

You can include html files with the @strong{include} command:

@verbatim
;; @include is the command name, not <@ include filename %>
<@include filename.html %>
@end verbatim

This will be expanded like this:

@verbatim
/current_toplevel/pub/filename.html
@end verbatim

@strong{NOTE:} Please make sure the included file is in the @strong{pub} directory in the application directory.

To refer to a CSS file:

@verbatim
<@css filename.css %>
@end verbatim

This will be expanded like this:

@verbatim
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/filename.css">
@end verbatim

To refer to a JS (javascript) file in the HTML head:

@verbatim
<@js filename.js %>
@end verbatim

This will be expanded like this:

@verbatim
<script type="text/javascript" src="/js/filename.js"> </script>
@end verbatim

To specify an icon for the domain:

@verbatim
<@icon favicon.ico %>
@end verbatim

This will be expanded like this:

@verbatim
<link rel="icon" href="/img/favicon.ico" type="image/x-icon">
@end verbatim

@node SXML Templates
@section SXML Templates
@anchor{#sxml-templates}
@uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SXML,SXML} is an alternative syntax for writing XML data, using the form of S-expressions.

SXML is to Scheme as JSON is to ECMAScript(the so-called Javascript). Maybe this explains it clearer.

One benefit of SXML is that it takes advantage of the quasiquote in Scheme. Please search in the internet "scheme quasiquote" for more details.

This is an SXML expression:

@verbatim
(tpl->response '(html (body (p (@ (id "content")) "hello world"))))
@end verbatim

The above would result the following HTML code:

@verbatim
<html><body><p id="content">hello world</p></body></html>
@end verbatim

Sometimes you may need quasiquote to refer to a variable, for example:

@verbatim
(let ((content "hello world"))
  (tpl->response `(html (body (p (@ (id "content")) ,content)))))
@end verbatim

Here, the "html" block is being quoted with the backtick, which in combination with a "," character before the variable name, makes the variable be referred to instead of just passing a string.

