@node DB init hooks
@section DB init hooks
@anchor{#db-init-hooks}
Sometimes you need to do some configurations before using DB, Artanis provide an API for that, you should put it to ENTRY file before run the server.

For example, assuming you're using MySQL/MariaDB, and you need to configure it to UTF-8, you should add these lines to you ENTRY file. Or if you're using minimal mode without application folder, just put it before running the server.

@verbatim
(run-when-DB-init!
 (lambda (conn)
   (DB-query conn "set names utf8;")))
@end verbatim

@strong{NOTE: Don't forget `!' here, it implies the side-effects in Scheme!}

@node DB connection pool
@section DB connection pool
@anchor{#db-connection-pool}
GNU Artanis will create a connection pool when you run @code{art work}. Its size is decided by @code{db.poolsize}. The pool is increasing by default for development and test. It is strongly recommended you to set @code{db.pool} to @code{fixed} when you deploy. The increasing pool will cause the effects that is similar to the memory leak. If you set it to fixed, then the request handler will be safely scheduled when there's no available DB connection, and it will be awake when it's available.

@node Migration
@section Migration
@anchor{#migration}
Migrations provide a way to do complicated modification of tables in a database by GNU Artanis. Here's an example.

First, draw a migration:

@verbatim
# art draw migration person
drawing    migration person
working    Migration `20151107040209_person.scm'
@end verbatim

You'll see something similar like above.

Then you'd edit the file db/migration/20151107040209_person.scm:

@verbatim
(migrate-up
 (create-table
  'person
  '(id auto (#:primary-key))
  '(name char-field (#:not-null #:maxlen 10))
  '(age tiny-integer (#:not-null))
  '(email char-field (#:maxlen 20))))

(migrate-down
 (drop-table 'person))
@end verbatim

Then you run the @strong{up} command for migration:

@verbatim
art migrate up person
@end verbatim

Then migrate-up function will be called, and this will create a table named @emph{person}:

@verbatim
+-------+---------------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+
| Field | Type                | Null | Key | Default | Extra          |
+-------+---------------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+
| id    | bigint(20) unsigned | NO   | PRI | NULL    | auto_increment |
| name  | varchar(10)         | NO   |     | NULL    |                |
| age   | tinyint(4)          | NO   |     | NULL    |                |
| email | varchar(20)         | YES  |     | NULL    |                |
+-------+---------------------+------+-----+---------+----------------+
@end verbatim

If you run the @strong{down} command of migration, as:

@verbatim
art migrate down person
@end verbatim

The table @emph{person} will be dropped.

@node ORM problem
@section ORM problem
@anchor{#orm-problem}
ORM stands for Object Relational Mapping, which is a popular approach to handle relational DB nowadays, especially for Object-Oriented Programming.

Of course, Guile has it's own Object System named @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/guile/manual/html_node/GOOPS.html#GOOPS,GOOPS}. Users can use OOP with it. And it's possible to implement ORM in GNU Artanis as well.

However, FP fans realized that they don't have to use OOP if they can use FP features reasonably.

Besides, there're some critics about ORM:

@itemize
@item
@uref{http://martinfowler.com/bliki/OrmHate.html,ORM Hate}

@item
@uref{http://blogs.tedneward.com/2006/06/26/The+Vietnam+Of+Computer+Science.aspx,Vietnam of Computer Science}

@item
@uref{http://blog.codinghorror.com/object-relational-mapping-is-the-vietnam-of-computer-science/,Object-Relational Mapping is the Vietnam of Computer Science}

@end itemize

Here are some known ways to solve ORM related problems:

@itemize
@item
1. @strong{@emph{Give up ORM}}.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
2. @strong{@emph{Give up relational storage model}}. Don't use a relational DB. Use another DB style, such as No-SQL. Well, this way is not cool when you must use a relational DB.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
3. @strong{@emph{Manual mapping}}. Write SQL code directly. It's fine sometimes. But the code increases when things get complicated. Refactoring and reusing would be worth to consider.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
4. @strong{@emph{Limited ORM}}. Limiting the utility of ORM. And use ORM to solve part of your work rather than whole, depends on you. This may avoid some problems.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
5. @strong{@emph{SQL related DSL}}. Design a new language. Microsoft's LINQ is such a case.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
6. @strong{@emph{Integration of relational concepts into frameworks}}. Well, harder than 5, but worth to try.
@end itemize

@itemize
@item
7. @strong{@emph{Stateless}}. This is the critical hit to counter complexity and unreliability.
@end itemize

Basically, GNU Artanis has no ORM yet, and maybe never will. GNU Artanis is trying to experiment new ways to solve the problems of ORM.

GNU Artanis provides several ways to complete this mission. All of them, are @strong{experimental} at present.

@itemize
@item
SSQL (1,3,5)

@item
FPRM (4,7)

@item
SQL Mapping (1,3,6)

@item
Plain SQL queries

@end itemize

@node SSQL
@section SSQL
@anchor{#ssql}
The concept of SSQL is to write SQL in @uref{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S-expression,s-expression}.

Usage:

@verbatim
(->sql sql-statement)
(where #:key val ... [literal string])
(having #:key val ... [literal string])
(/or conds ...)
(/and conds ...)
@end verbatim

For example:

@verbatim
(->sql select * from 'Persons (where #:city "Tokyo"))
(->sql select '(age name) from 'Persons (where "age < 30"))
@end verbatim

The SQL update command is quite different to SQL grammar. Example:

@verbatim
(->sql update 'table set (list (list phone_number "08080001234")) (where #:name "john"))
@end verbatim

