@node Map DB table
@subsection Map DB table
@anchor{#map-db-table}
This step will generate an new instance (as a closure) mapped to database table or view. In ORM, it is often called an @uref{http://www.martinfowler.com/eaaCatalog/activeRecord.html,Active Record.} It maps the database view to a class object.

There are two main differences to SSQL:

@itemize
@item
FPRM doesn't create an object for each table. It maps the whole database, and generates an SQL for each table as you use it. So it might be lighter compared to an ORM object.
@item
FPRM doesn't maintain any states at all. It's stateless as an object (Not in the database).
@end itemize

These two points may decrease the power of FPRM, but our main philosophy in GNU Artanis is that

@itemize
@item
@emph{The best way to control DB is SQL, don't bother with other guile schemes.}
@end itemize

That means we're not going to develop a complicated ORM in GNU Artanis, but a promising way to interact with SQL easily. This is what @emph{SQL Mapping} provided. FPRM aims to reduce states & complexity to provide reliability. And SQL-Mapping will provide a convenient way to handle complex SQL queries for better performance and security (SQL-Injection, etc).

@verbatim
(define m (map-table-from-DB rc/conn))
@end verbatim

@strong{rc/conn} can be a route-context or a DB connection.

map-table-from-DB returns a function, named @strong{m} here for simplicity.

