@node Plain SQL queries
@section Plain SQL queries
@anchor{#plain-sql-queries}
Using GNU Artanis, you can also drop to a lower level of database interaction and write raw SQL queries. This can be useful for complex operations involving multiple tables, @code{JOIN} statements, @code{GROUP} statements and the likes.

We will assume your route context (in the controller) is named @code{rc}, you can open a DB connection with @code{(DB-open rc)}. If you write single statement queries, you don't need to terminate them with a semicolon @code{;} but if you write multiple expressions in one go then you will need one.

See some example queries:

@verbatim
;; this will fetch a list of rows (a row is an alist of string column name to value)
(DB-get-all-rows (DB-query (DB-open rc) "SELECT * FROM products ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 42"))

;; this will update some row
(DB-query (DB-open rc) "UPDATE products SET name = 'High-end Lisp Machine', updated_at = 1749805637 WHERE id = '50f11747-8714-4159-92e5-ff876f96a65a'")
@end verbatim

@node RESTful API
@chapter RESTful API
@anchor{#restful-api}
GNU Artanis provides a command @code{art api} to generate RESTful API skeleton, and the API version can be managed.

@verbatim
art api -c

creating   restful API v1
create     app/api/v1.scm
@end verbatim

The generated file @strong{app/api/v1.scm} will contain such a line:

@verbatim
(define-restful-api v1) ; DO NOT REMOVE THIS LINE!!!
@end verbatim

@strong{v1} is the default version, if you may specify your prefered API version, for example, @strong{v3}:

@verbatim
art api -c -v v3
@end verbatim

@code{-c} means to create.

You should use @code{api-define} to define the RESTful API:

@verbatim
(api-define rule handler)
@end verbatim

@code{api-define} is an overloaded method of the controller define function. So you may use it like what you do with the controller in MVC. Here's a pseudo example:

@verbatim
(define (auth-err)
  (scm->json `((status ,status) (reason "Auth error!"))))

(api-define article/list
  (options #:mime 'json #:with-auth auth-err)
  (lambda (rc) ...))
@end verbatim

Although the registered URL is @code{"article/list"}, the actual API would be @code{"v1/article/list"}, depends on the specified API version.

