@node Cache APIs
@section Cache APIs
@anchor{#cache-apis}
You can use @code{#:cache mode} to define a URL rule handler.

@verbatim
(get "/certain-rule" #:cache mode
     (lambda (rc) ...))
@end verbatim

@strong{@emph{NOTE}}: the default value of "maxage" (3600 seconds) is defined by @code{cache.maxage} in @code{/etc/artanis/artanis.conf}.

@strong{mode} can be:

@itemize
@item
@code{#t} to enable caching the page.
@item
@code{#f} to disable caching the page explicitly. It's the default value.
@item
@code{('static [maxage <- 3600])} to be used for static files. The URL rule must be a real path to a static file.
@item
@code{(filename [maxage <- 3600])} to cache a static file. This is useful when you don't want to reveal the actual path of the static file, but use a fake URL for it.
@item
@code{('public filename [maxage <- 3600])} to allow proxies cache the content of specified static file. If HTTP authentication is required, responses are automatically set to "private".
@item
@code{('private filename [maxage <- 3600])} to not allow proxies cache the content of specified static file.
@end itemize

Let's set a simple cache setting for dynamic content:

@verbatim
(get "/new" #:cache #t
     (lambda (rc)
       (:cache rc "hello world")))
@end verbatim

If you want to cache a static file, and permit proxies cache the content:

@verbatim
(get "/hide" #:cache '(public "/some.html")
     (lambda (rc)
       (:cache rc)))
@end verbatim

But, if your current URL rule is used for authentication (once you use @code{#:auth}), the cache will be changed to @strong{private} even if you specify @strong{public}.

@verbatim
(get "/pauth"
  #:auth `(basic ,(lambda (rc u p) (and (string=? u "nala")
                                        (string=? p "123"))))
  #:cache '(public "/some.html") ; will be changed to 'private' forcely.
  (lambda (rc) (:cache rc)))
@end verbatim

