@node What is shortcuts?
@section What is shortcuts?
@anchor{#what-is-shortcuts}
@emph{shortcuts} are a series of special functions. They're used to simplify the complex operations, according to the configuration specified by the related keyword, set after a URL-rule.

It was named @emph{OHT} which stands for @emph{Optional Handler Table}, which indicates the basic principle to be implemented. But it was too hard to remember. So let's just call it @emph{shortcut}.

Anyway, you may find them in the module @uref{https://gitlab.com/NalaGinrut/artanis/blob/master/artanis/oht.scm,(artanis oht)}.

It's good practice to use @emph{shortcuts} as possible and avoid calling low-level APIs.

Each shortcut consists of 2 parts: @strong{config} and @strong{apply}.

@strong{config} is to configure a certain service for the specific URL rule. This configuration will only be availble to this URL rule, and independent to other registered URL rules.

@strong{apply} is used to call specific functions related to your configuration in the @strong{config} step. The first argument of the @strong{apply} method must be a @code{route-context} (@emph{route context}).

@node Database connection
@section Database connection
@anchor{#database-connection}
This is a useful feature to use when you connect to a database. The shortcut provides a way to interact with the raw connection. The connection is fetched from the connection pool, which is created at GNU Artanis's start up.

@verbatim
;; config
#:conn #t

;; apply
(:conn <route-context> [sql])
@end verbatim

@itemize
@item
The second argument is optional, if it's missing, then @code{:conn} will return the raw connection after applying @code{(:conn rc)}.
@itemize
@item
NOTE: If you haven't set @code{#:conn #t}, and applied @code{(:conn rc)}, then @code{(rc-conn rc)} will return @code{#f}. This is why you shouldn't use low-level @code{(rc-conn rc)}.
@end itemize

@item
If you pass a second argument, it should be a valid SQL query string. The returned value is described in @emph{DB connection pool}.
@itemize
@item
You can create the SQL query string with @emph{SSQL}.
@end itemize

@end itemize

