@node Websocket introduction
@section Websocket introduction
@anchor{#websocket-introduction}
Websockets are becoming more and more important for modern web development. GNU Artanis is trying to provide an industrial strength and efficient Websocket implementation. Websockets are important for GNU Artanis's design. Please see @emph{Principles} for more details.

@node Websocket basic usage
@section Websocket basic usage
@anchor{#websocket-basic-usage}
In GNU Artanis, a Websocket handling is triggered by setting it on a specific URL. You should use @code{#:websocket} to configure the Websocket. Here's the API definition:

@verbatim
#:websocket (proto protocol-name ['inexclusive])
@end verbatim

@strong{'inexclusive} is optional. By default, each Websocket connection only servs one client. However, sometimes we do need to multicast the messages to several clients. Enable @strong{'inexclusive} is the easiest way, but it may cause the similar issue to file-description-leaking. There're two suggestions:

@itemize
@item
Set and check security token to prevent malicious programs establish massive connections.
@item
If you want to do muticasting as in pub/sub, then use different token or named-pipe to subscribe. And maintain a subscribers table for multicasting.
@end itemize

Here's a simple example for common cases:

@verbatim
(use-modules (artanis artanis))

(get "/echo" #:websocket '(proto echo)
     (lambda (rc)
       (:websocket rc 'payload)))

(run #:port 3000)
@end verbatim

In this simple test, we choose the simplest @strong{echo} protocol of the Websocket. This will return back the string sent from the client. Let's also write a simple javascript function for the web frontend:

@verbatim
function WebSocketTest()
{
    if ("WebSocket" in window)
    {
        document.write("<p>WebSocket is supported by your Browser!</p>");

        // Let us open a web socket
        var ws = new WebSocket("ws://localhost:3000/echo");

        ws.onopen = function()
        {
            // Web Socket is connected, send data using send()
            ws.send("hello world");
            document.write("<p>Message is sent...</p>");
        };

        ws.onmessage = function (evt)
        {
            var received_msg = evt.data;
            document.write("<p>hello welcome...</p>");
        };

        ws.onclose = function()
        {
            // websocket is closed.
            document.write("<p>Connection is closed...</p>");
        };

        window.onbeforeunload = function(event) {
            socket.close();
        };
    }
    else
    {
        // Your browser doesn't support WebSockets
        document.write("<p>WebSocket NOT supported by your Browser!</p>");
    }
}
@end verbatim

@node Websocket named-pipe
@section Websocket named-pipe
@anchor{#websocket-named-pipe}
Artanis provides the named-pipe based on Websocket, which is very useful to interact between the client and server. @emph{NOTE: The Websocket named-pipe is very useful to implement server-push messaging.}

Here is the critical API:

@verbatim
(named-pipe-subscribe <route-context>)
@end verbatim

Let's try a simple example:

@verbatim
(get "/robot" #:websocket '(proto echo) named-pipe-subscribe)
@end verbatim

Here we register a WebAPI named @code{"/robot"}, and configure it a Websocket API by @code{#:websocket '(proto echo)}. As you may see, we specify its protocol to a simple echo protocal, it is to say, it will redirect what it receives. Each time it receives a message, it will redirect the message to the specified named-pipe, and the subscriber of that named-pipe will get the message instantly. The name of the pipe is specified by the client like this:

@verbatim
var ws = new WebSocket("ws://localhost:3000/robot?artanis_named_pipe=robot-1");
@end verbatim

The query-string @code{"artanis_named_pipe"} is a special key in Artanis, you MUST use this key to specify the pipe name. Here we specify the pipe name as @code{"robot-1"}.

Now we setup the named-pipe, however, we still need to setup another WebAPI to let the client send message:

@verbatim
(get "/welcome/:whom/:what" #:websocket 'send-only
     (lambda (rc)
       (:websocket rc 'send (params rc "whom") (params rc "what"))
       "ok"))
@end verbatim

The configure @code{"#:websocket 'send-only"} means this API is only for sending, so that it's half-duplex. And another critical Websocket API here:

@verbatim
(:websocket <route-context> 'send <pipe-name> <data>)
@end verbatim

Each time you send data from the WebAPI, for example:

@verbatim
curl localhost:3000/welcome/robot-1/nala
@end verbatim

In our simple example of @uref{https://gitlab.com/NalaGinrut/artanis/blob/master/examples/websocket-named-pipe.html,Websocket named-pipe test}, you should run The named-pipe will receive the message @code{"nala"}, and the page on the browser will print @code{"hello welcome...nala"} instantly.

